  "prompt": "Is it likely that stem cell tooth regeneration will be possible by next year (2017)?",
  "response": "As of now, stem cell tooth regeneration has not been fully realized as a clinical treatment. While there has been significant research in the field of regenerative dentistry, including the use of stem cells for tooth regeneration, translating these findings into practical, safe, and effective treatments can take considerable time.\n\nBy 2017, significant advancements were made in understanding the biology of tooth development and the potential use of stem cells, but fully functional tooth regeneration for clinical use was still in the research phase. Many challenges remained, including ensuring proper integration with surrounding tissues, functionality, and long-term viability.\n\nTherefore, it is unlikely that stem cell tooth regeneration would be widely available or clinically feasible by 2017. For the most current developments in this area, it would be best to consult recent research studies or expert reviews in regenerative dentistry.",
